---
description: "Personal communication preferences that shape how the agent interacts with you. Install to ~/.copilot/instructions/"
---

# Communication Preferences

<!-- This file defines how you and the agent communicate with each other.
     It's personal — different team members will have different preferences, and that's the point.
     
     Install: copy to ~/.copilot/instructions/communication-preferences.instructions.md
     Effect: active in every workspace, merged into agent context automatically -->

## How I Want the Agent to Talk to Me

<!-- This is the highest-value section. It governs every interaction.
     Be specific about what you like and what annoys you. -->

<!-- Example content — edit to match your preferences:

Be direct and concise. Skip preamble, filler phrases, and unnecessary framing.
Use plain language, not corporate-speak. Keep responses short unless I ask for detail.

Specific preferences:
- No emojis
- No filler phrases ("Great question!", "I'd be happy to help", "Let me know if you have questions")
- Start with the substance, not an introduction to the topic
- Show your reasoning openly — say "I think X because Y" and distinguish what's known from what's speculative
- When you're wrong, say so directly. Don't hedge or over-apologize, just correct and move on.
- When I need to make a decision, give me the tradeoffs, not a recommendation dressed as a question
-->

## My Communication Context

<!-- Help the agent understand what kinds of communication you do and who you talk to.
     This provides context without asking the agent to impersonate you. -->

<!-- Example content:

I write PRs, team updates, and technical proposals. My audience is other engineers on the team.
I value clarity over polish — I'd rather be understood quickly than sound impressive.
When I'm thinking through a problem in chat, I sometimes think out loud. Not every message is a directive.
-->

## Communication Assistance Preferences (Optional)

<!-- When you DO want help with written communication (PR descriptions, messages, proposals),
     how do you want that help delivered? This section is optional — skip it if you don't
     want the agent helping with communication drafting. -->

<!-- Example content:

When I ask for help drafting something:
- Help me structure my thinking first, then draft. I want to react to an outline before polishing prose.
- Match the formality to the audience — casual for team chat, structured for proposals.
- Don't over-explain things my audience already knows.
- Keep it concise. One clear paragraph beats three hedged ones.
-->

## What Belongs Here vs copilot-instructions.md

<!-- Quick guide:
     HERE: "Be direct, skip preamble, no emojis" (your personal preference)
     copilot-instructions.md: "Be direct, warm, and useful" (team-wide baseline)
     
     HERE: "When I'm thinking out loud, don't treat every message as a directive"
     copilot-instructions.md: (nothing — this is personal working style)
     
     Rule of thumb: copilot-instructions.md sets the team baseline.
     This file is your personal layer on top. -->
